README.md
     1‚Üí# Archived project. No maintenance. 
     3‚ÜíThis project is not maintained anymore and is archived. Feel free to fork and
     4‚Üímake your own changes if needed. For more detail read my blog post: [Taking an indefinite sabbatical from my projects](https://arslan.io/2018/10/09/taking-an-indefinite-sabbatical-from-my-projects/)
     5‚Üí
     6‚ÜíThanks to everyone for their valuable feedback and contributions.
     7‚Üí
     8‚Üí# Structs
    10‚ÜíStructs contains various utilities to work with Go (Golang) structs. It was
    11‚Üíinitially used by me to convert a struct into a `map[string]interface{}`. With
    12‚Üítime I've added other utilities for structs.  It's basically a high level
    13‚Üípackage based on primitives from the reflect package. Feel free to add new
    14‚Üífunctions or improve the existing code.
    15‚Üí
    16‚Üí## Install
    18‚Üí```bash
    19‚Üígo get github.com/fatih/structs
    20‚Üí```
    21‚Üí
    22‚Üí## Usage and Examples
    24‚ÜíJust like the standard lib `strings`, `bytes` and co packages, `structs` has
    25‚Üímany global functions to manipulate or organize your struct data. Lets define
    26‚Üíand declare a struct:
    27‚Üí
    28‚Üí```go
    29‚Üítype Server struct {
    30‚Üí	Name        string `json:"name,omitempty"`
    31‚Üí	ID          int
    32‚Üí	Enabled     bool
    33‚Üí	users       []string // not exported
    34‚Üí	http.Server          // embedded
    35‚Üí}
    36‚Üí
    37‚Üíserver := &Server{
    38‚Üí	Name:    "gopher",
    39‚Üí	ID:      123456,
    40‚Üí	Enabled: true,
    41‚Üí}
    42‚Üí```
    43‚Üí
    44‚Üí```go
    45‚Üí// Convert a struct to a map[string]interface{}
    46‚Üí// => {"Name":"gopher", "ID":123456, "Enabled":true}
    47‚Üím := structs.Map(server)
    48‚Üí
    49‚Üí// Convert the values of a struct to a []interface{}
    50‚Üí// => ["gopher", 123456, true]
    51‚Üív := structs.Values(server)
    52‚Üí
    53‚Üí// Convert the names of a struct to a []string
    54‚Üí// (see "Names methods" for more info about fields)
    55‚Üín := structs.Names(server)
    56‚Üí
    57‚Üí// Convert the values of a struct to a []*Field
    58‚Üí// (see "Field methods" for more info about fields)
    59‚Üíf := structs.Fields(server)
    60‚Üí
    61‚Üí// Return the struct name => "Server"
    62‚Üín := structs.Name(server)
    63‚Üí
    64‚Üí// Check if any field of a struct is initialized or not.
    65‚Üíh := structs.HasZero(server)
    66‚Üí
    67‚Üí// Check if all fields of a struct is initialized or not.
    68‚Üíz := structs.IsZero(server)
    69‚Üí
    70‚Üí// Check if server is a struct or a pointer to struct
    71‚Üíi := structs.IsStruct(server)
    72‚Üí```
    73‚Üí
    74‚Üí### Struct methods
    76‚ÜíThe structs functions can be also used as independent methods by creating a new
    77‚Üí`*structs.Struct`. This is handy if you want to have more control over the
    78‚Üístructs (such as retrieving a single Field).
    79‚Üí
    80‚Üí```go
    81‚Üí// Create a new struct type:
    82‚Üís := structs.New(server)
    83‚Üí
    84‚Üím := s.Map()              // Get a map[string]interface{}
    85‚Üív := s.Values()           // Get a []interface{}
    86‚Üíf := s.Fields()           // Get a []*Field
    87‚Üín := s.Names()            // Get a []string
    88‚Üíf := s.Field(name)        // Get a *Field based on the given field name
    89‚Üíf, ok := s.FieldOk(name)  // Get a *Field based on the given field name
    90‚Üín := s.Name()             // Get the struct name
    91‚Üíh := s.HasZero()          // Check if any field is uninitialized
    92‚Üíz := s.IsZero()           // Check if all fields are uninitialized
    93‚Üí```
    94‚Üí
    95‚Üí### Field methods
    97‚ÜíWe can easily examine a single Field for more detail. Below you can see how we
    98‚Üíget and interact with various field methods:
    99‚Üí
   100‚Üí
   101‚Üí```go
   102‚Üís := structs.New(server)
   103‚Üí
   104‚Üí// Get the Field struct for the "Name" field
   105‚Üíname := s.Field("Name")
   106‚Üí
   107‚Üí// Get the underlying value,  value => "gopher"
   108‚Üívalue := name.Value().(string)
   109‚Üí
   110‚Üí// Set the field's value
   111‚Üíname.Set("another gopher")
   112‚Üí
   113‚Üí// Get the field's kind, kind =>  "string"
   114‚Üíname.Kind()
   115‚Üí
   116‚Üí// Check if the field is exported or not
   117‚Üíif name.IsExported() {
   118‚Üí	fmt.Println("Name field is exported")
   119‚Üí}
   120‚Üí
   121‚Üí// Check if the value is a zero value, such as "" for string, 0 for int
   122‚Üíif !name.IsZero() {
   123‚Üí	fmt.Println("Name is initialized")
   124‚Üí}
   125‚Üí
   126‚Üí// Check if the field is an anonymous (embedded) field
   127‚Üíif !name.IsEmbedded() {
   128‚Üí	fmt.Println("Name is not an embedded field")
   129‚Üí}
   130‚Üí
   131‚Üí// Get the Field's tag value for tag name "json", tag value => "name,omitempty"
   132‚ÜítagValue := name.Tag("json")
   133‚Üí```
   134‚Üí
   135‚ÜíNested structs are supported too:
   136‚Üí
   137‚Üí```go
   138‚ÜíaddrField := s.Field("Server").Field("Addr")
   139‚Üí
   140‚Üí// Get the value for addr
   141‚Üía := addrField.Value().(string)
   142‚Üí
   143‚Üí// Or get all fields
   144‚ÜíhttpServer := s.Field("Server").Fields()
   145‚Üí```
   146‚Üí
